WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:06.160
Hey everyone. I'm excited to go last because I have a slide on motivation, but I think the last

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:12.640
three talks really kind of drove the point home. So thanks for coming to my talk, Package Management

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:18.799
for Data Scientists. Just as an introduction, my name is Tyler Finethy. I'm an engineering

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:24.000
manager at posit working on the Package Manager product. I'm also a member of the R Consortium

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.959
Working Group for Repositories, and I have about a decade of software engineering experience.

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:33.279
I also started in data science running into a lot of the problems that were discussed today.

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:40.240
So as an overview, I'll go through some motivation and scope. We'll talk software

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:45.680
package basics. I'll go through a couple challenges, solutions, and ways to prevent

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:50.400
those challenges from appearing in the first place. Finally, we'll end with some key takeaways.

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:56.720
So if you've ever lost your mind installing package dependencies in a new environment and

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:04.800
things blow up, running an old script and you get a little frustrated, hearing it works on

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:09.440
my machine by maybe a co-worker and then you can't get it running, this talk's probably for you.

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:17.839
So just for scope and focus, these are going to be language agnostic challenges and solutions,

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:24.000
but the examples will be in R and Python. Challenges are typically not unique to one

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.400
language, but the good thing is that means that neither are the solutions or the approaches we

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:34.239
can take to those challenges. And finally, I'm just going to use package library dependency

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:39.199
interchangeably, because once you try to figure out what is what in different languages, it gets

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:47.599
a little chaotic. So what is a package? The way I kind of define a package is it's an encapsulated

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:53.199
piece of code or software. These are shared or installed to enhance or extend existing

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:59.519
functionality. So in R, you use install.packages. In Python, you might use pip install or conda or

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:06.800
pipenv. You have a lot more options. And then some examples, we use ggplot2 to create graphs and

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:14.880
plots and requests to make HTTP requests. So to make sure everyone's on the same page, we install

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:21.759
a package using install.packages. We use a library command in R to import a package, and then we can

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:28.479
use that package in our code to run the functions, in this case, creating a scatterplot. Same thing

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:34.880
in Python, we install a package. This happens at the command line in Python using pip. We can import

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:41.119
that package, and then we can use it in our code. So the first challenge that I want to talk about

00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:46.720
is the conflicting versions challenge. We talked about this a little bit with snapshots, but

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:53.919
packages generally use other packages. So this is an example of a dependency tree. It's a little

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:59.759
dated, but the concepts are still there. Say we want to install some package. We call that a direct

00:02:59.759 --> 00:03:06.720
dependency. That package, just like we want to enhance our software, it wants to enhance itself

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:12.880
and not have to do all the little things. So it has indirect dependencies. The thing that we really

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:19.440
want to focus on here is packages that have many lines going to them. So those are packages with a

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:25.440
number of reverse dependencies like we see down here in the bottom. So with that information,

00:03:26.559 --> 00:03:32.960
we can look at a conflicting versions example. So say we have package A, and that relies on some

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:39.600
version of Rcpp, call it 1.0.6. This is all good and dandy until we want package B,

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:50.160
which requires Rcpp 1.0.7. So that probably won't work. But what should we do here? We can say

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:59.600
we'll just always use Rcpp 1.0.6 for package A, and we'll use 1.0.7 for package B. A lot of

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:03.919
languages won't actually allow that, but even if they did, it would be pretty hard to manage.

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:09.919
We could potentially upgrade package A, but that will depend if the author has actually upgraded

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:17.279
package A in GitHub or on CRAN. And then we could try downgrading package B, but you run into the

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:26.480
same problem. That author might not have a version that works with Rcpp 1.0.6. So this fictitious

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:34.239
example comes from Stack Overflow. I found this annotation hub installation of Rcpp 1.0.6 is

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:41.600
already loaded, but you know you need 1.0.7. So looking at the solutions from Stack Overflow,

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:50.000
first one user recommended using renv. That ended up working for the person who ran into the issue,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
but at the end of the day that was just downgrading annotation hub.

00:04:54.799 --> 00:04:59.600
The next user said, update all of the installed packages, delete all of your other files, create

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:04.559
a new environment, and that solves your problem. I don't know if you want to do that every single

00:05:04.559 --> 00:05:10.399
time. And then same thing, upgrade R, which is basically a new environment, and then everything

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:15.119
should work for you again when you install all your packages. So we should know how to solve

00:05:15.119 --> 00:05:21.679
these things, but we should learn to prevent them in the first place. And I have renv on this slide,

00:05:22.559 --> 00:05:29.279
but maybe it should say slushy. We should use tools to create reproducible environments. So

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:35.519
we have renv lock, we have requirements.txt in Python, and then we should use snapshots for

00:05:35.519 --> 00:05:42.000
package installation. So mini-cran is one R package that you can use to grab subsets of cran.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.600
Bandersnatch is one in Python, and then it was mentioned a couple times previously,

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:52.320
but we also have deposit public package manager. If you haven't seen that before,

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:56.480
this is what the view kind of looks like as you're selecting a snapshot that you

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.200
want to always install packages from. This works really well on the R ecosystem,

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:06.320
because those packages on any given date are more likely to be compatible with one another,

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:10.480
and then it works really well in Python, because if a package is randomly deleted from PyPI,

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:14.239
which happens sometimes when authors get mad, then you also get those.

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:18.399
So the next challenge I want to talk about are system dependencies.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:27.279
Like packages also use other packages, packages also use other software. So you can have R that

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:33.920
relies on Python using reticulate, but you can have R and Python that rely on a bunch of different

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:39.440
pieces of software. So your Python code might only work on Windows, your R code might only

00:06:40.399 --> 00:06:46.959
work with a specific version of C++, Python might require OpenSSL, whatever it is,

00:06:46.959 --> 00:06:49.600
and so this can make it pretty hard to move these things around.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:57.839
So as an example again, say we want to install the cryptography package in Python.

00:06:59.519 --> 00:07:05.519
So we run pip install cryptography, and then we get some esoteric error that we don't have

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:14.320
something installed. So what should we do now? We can google how do you install GCC and then try

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:19.440
this command again and hope it works. We can try to find a binary that's pre-installed and maybe

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:26.640
that will solve our problem. And this again comes from Stack Overflow, I actually found a ton of

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:32.640
these. And then looking at the solutions, if you're on Windows, you'll need to make sure you

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:38.880
have OpenSSL installed. For Debian or Ubuntu, you need to run some other command.

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:44.959
And there were more solutions for Mac OS, RHEL, Fedora, Raspberry Pi, etc.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:51.920
So again, we can prevent this from happening in the first place. We can use tools to easily manage

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:57.040
and recreate environments. We can use Conda, Docker, PipM, even Workbench works for this.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:05.279
We can use pre-compiled binaries when possible. So PyPI will serve wheels which differ by package,

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:08.959
so some packages will have pre-compiled wheels and other packages won't.

00:08:09.679 --> 00:08:15.359
Crayon generally serves R packages built for Windows and Mac OS. R-Universe also

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:21.359
serves packages built for Windows and Mac OS. Public Package Manager adds some Linux distributions,

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:26.640
but in some of these cases, we still need system dependencies installed for things to work.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:32.960
There's no kind of silver bullet here. That's all I wanted to do in terms of challenges today.

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:37.760
If you want to dig deeper, I have a blog post called Challenges in Package Management.

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:44.479
I put the Public Package Manager URL there. And then if you really kind of want to get into the

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:50.640
nitty-gritty, I watched this talk called How Can Package Managers Handle ABI and Compatibility in

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:57.119
C++ and that was pretty intense, so check it out. In terms of takeaways,

00:08:59.119 --> 00:09:04.640
every time you create a new R or Python script, you should also create a lockfile of requirements.txt.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:08.960
You know, if you get used to this, then you're not going to run into that thing where

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:11.679
six months later you try to run code and nothing works again.

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:18.080
Consider looking at tools like Docker to handle environments and avoid some of those other

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:23.440
problems. And then if you're a package author, define your versions and system dependencies for

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:34.320
others. So whenever you see this, I want you to be asking, where's my lockfile? Cool. Thank you.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:40.880
Thanks, Tyler. We do have some time for questions. Again, it's Slido. Can we put the

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:48.000
yeah, posit with Slido-B there for Ballroom B. One question here is, what do you recommend

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.559
for package management in an air-gapped environment that is needed for working with sensitive data?

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.400
Well, Package Manager works in a lot of different ways.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:07.039
Package Manager works in an air-gapped environment, so that would probably be my first.

00:10:07.039 --> 00:10:13.200
Thanks for setting that one up for us. Yeah. Minicran and I think Bandersnatch also work.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:18.479
If you're just working in either R or Python and you need something easy, you can download those.

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:24.479
Any other questions that people have? You can just raise your hand at this point if you'd like to.

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:26.479
Sure.

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:39.919
Yeah, that's a good question. I mean, I think whenever you're making decisions around

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:44.400
locking and how permissible to be in terms of requirements, you really have to look at

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:51.200
how sensitive is your data, how worried are you about vulnerabilities and those sorts of things.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:57.760
And if you just really want things to work in six months, you know, I would pin to a specific version

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:02.239
and then, you know, you can add tests and as tests pass, you can try to like...

00:11:02.239 --> 00:11:07.760
like GitHub now has the dependabot that will look at versions and upgrade them until at least you

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:12.320
can get some workflow to confirm that things are still working instead of just relying that the

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:17.760
package is going to work six months later or something. In my experience, at least in the R

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:22.320
world, it's been fairly common that people just do greater than or equal to at the one that works,

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:26.799
right? And typically that's the CRAN version. It does seem slightly more common in the Python world

00:11:26.799 --> 00:11:31.119
that people will either pin to a specific version or they will sometimes pin down to like a previous

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:35.440
version if they know that the new one somehow doesn't work with their thing. That does cause

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:38.239
some issues though. So anyone else?

00:11:43.599 --> 00:11:49.200
Okay, thanks so much, Tyler.

